As a college athlete, @em_durgin only made one NCAA Cross Country Championship, where she finished 115th.
 
Now she’s headed to Australia to represent Team @usatf at the @worldathletics Cross Country Championships.

📸 @justinbritton

2023 ❤️🇺🇸
Here is the thing…my first race post NYC was going to be extremely nerve-racking. I know I know one “bad” day doesn’t define you. But I had put so much into my first marathon build it was a tough one to move on from.

After a month off and a lot of physical / mental recovery I was ready to look forward. I called Terrence Jan 2 & said “let’s run US cross.” We hadn’t put together a concrete plan yet, but I knew cross was the best way to start the year. He said “guess we need to start working out” 😆

I was excited to workout. I was excited to race, and I was ready to compete again.

SO if you are coming off a “bad” day take your time, but TRUST me when you do decide to compete you’ll be stronger & it will feel just like you remember. 🏃‍♀️🔥

Major bonus my 2 @adidas teammates also made their first world team! 🇺🇸❤️🇺🇸 We are excited to represent USA!

Pc @justinbritton

🇺🇸🇺🇸🇺🇸
Fun little weekend trip to Richmond. Thanks for joining Dad ❤️

Pc @kevmofoto

What’s that great saying we never want to hear in the moment, but then it ends up coming true?… “it’s a minor setback for a major comeback.”
Injuries are never fun & seem to come when you least expect them and as hard as we try you cannot outsmart them! 
After a few days of cross training I knew something more was off & the MRI showed an early stress reaction. 
Of course I was like GREAT I’ll just hammer the cross training for a few days and I’ll be ready to rock at World Cross!! 🥳🇺🇸 WELL, after talking to medical professionals, my coach & support team….this is where you can’t outsmart the injury. 
I would run the risk of hurting myself worse by running on a stress injury so we (ok, not really we my body made this for us) had to pull out of World Cross Country in 2 weeks.
This has been tough to come to terms with, but I know the US 🇺🇸 is sending a great group of women to Australia.🔥
For Me-it’s time to make my weaknesses my strengths over the next few weeks & watch out world 🌍🌏 because the major comeback is brewing!😅🙏🏻

Be patient.
Be kind to yourself.
❤️

pc @kevmofoto

Spent the past 2 week in San Diego 🌞

Originally this trip was going to be all about getting in great workouts & miles.
Instead we spent the time jump starting injury rehab. 
This included: 
- Evaluating / building a new strength program with Terrence
- Treatment & laser sessions by @novosathlete
- Pool & bike cross training 
- Hot yoga at @hotroom_yoga 🔥
- great sunsets & dinner in Encinitas 😊

Now spending some time in Phoenix bc everyone knows lap swimming outdoors is way more enjoyable 😎🌊

Here is your reminder 
to be present✨

These past few weeks I’ve had to work on my mindset A LOT. 

At first I was just trying to tick off the days & speed up time. 

Lately, I have just focused fully on enjoying the moment I am in.

By doing this my body & mind are feeling so much stronger! 
CRAZY, right? 😉

✌🏻February. 

More selfies / happy moments from the past 28 days 😊

‼️EXCITING NEWS‼️
I’m back running & working out 👟
The body and mind are feeling good and I have some fun races lined up 👀👀
Perfect timing to put my #ULTRABOOST on. Let’s go 🔥🔥

#impossibleisnothing
#ULTRABOOST
#createdwithadidas

Been doing a lot more of this lately🤩
Coming back from time away from running is always interesting…
I use the word interesting because it’s wild how your body just remembers how to do it! Just like riding a bike…you don’t lose it, baby!!!🚴‍♀️

SO if you are going through an injury or just taking time off from running right now, and are worried about getting back into it. DON’T. Because, trust me when I said you’ll remember how to run!!!🏃‍♀️❤️

Pc @kevmofoto

26.2 ✅
I am officially a marathoner!
I had a great experience out on the streets of Toronto yesterday at @towaterfront42k ! 
Going into this race we wanted to get my body & mind use to the distance.  No time goal, no pacer, I just wanted to run the miles feeling strong (in an ideal world negative split the second half, but Toronto winds decided that wasn’t happening 😅 even if I felt like I was moving faster!)
I ended up running 2:26.46 to hit the Olympic standard, which was a nice bonus! 

So of course I have to end with…

“Success is not final; failure is not fatal: It is the courage to continue that counts." — Winston S. Churchill 
😊 #adidasrunning #marathon #toronto 

Pc @jkh_photo
